    {
      "id": "8e820ee85e78a4b86698a9722c0981172674fe61",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2014-07-10 15:28:51.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1\n\nNote that if you use wait_for_completion_interruptible() the process can also be interrupted by <ctrl-z> or sigalarm or other signals. I don't know that anyone would want their IO to fail when they hit <ctrl-z>. \n\nThat is why we created l_wait_event() - so that the process could not be interrupted while there was still a chance to complete the initial RPC, but the process became interruptible after the client had timed out. \n\nIf CLIO will handle the resend of the write if it is interrupted, then wait_for_completion_interruptible() is fine, otherwise the current patch with wait_for_completion_killable() is safer - the user cannot expect that the IO is finished if the program is killed.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "664f82a99fc4b6204f3063eac6dab7a8ee6d2e4e",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
        "name": "Maloo",
        "email": "maloo@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2014-07-10 16:29:40.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nTests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 6.5/x86_64: (https://testing.hpdd.intel.com/test_sessions/e10190c0-084c-11e4-9cc2-5254006e85c2).  Ran 8 tests.  1 tests failed: sanity.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "6405d4917c48760d087402b42dc5d8a2b6543a10",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
        "name": "Maloo",
        "email": "maloo@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2014-07-10 16:32:24.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nTests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 6.5/x86_64: (https://testing.hpdd.intel.com/test_sessions/acef5e7c-084f-11e4-8e5a-5254006e85c2).  Ran 13 tests.  No failures.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "cad071bf1ffc8aac19ffde975895ff5cf52300f7",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 4,
        "name": "Jinshan Xiong",
        "email": "jinshan.xiong@intel.com",
        "username": "Jay",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2014-07-10 17:42:11.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\n\"Note that if you use wait_for_completion_interruptible() the process can also be interrupted by <ctrl-z> or sigalarm or other signals. I don't know that anyone would want their IO to fail when they hit <ctrl-z>.\"\n\nFor most harmless signals, the kernel will restart the syscall as we return ERESTARTSYS here. For signals w/ handlers, they will be restarted if SA_RESTART is set w/ signal handers. Therefore it would be fine - please correct me if I understood it wrong.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "fe483c30ccccdb092cab59deab851deeea630221",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
